The paper deals with constraint satisfaction problems, which are a fundamental topic in computer science. The focus is on problems parameterized above or below tight bounds, which suggests that the paper may belong to the computational complexity (cs.CC) or data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. The use of linear equations and Boolean formulas in the examples suggests that the paper may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The mention of "order constraint satisfaction problems" suggests that the paper may also belong to the discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. Finally, the discussion of results obtained in the last few years suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
